30. repom· deterioribus] This has some- times been translated as if Horace meant that true virtue would not suffer itself to be replaced by false, or virtue of a lower sort. I rather think he means that true virtue, when it has once been lost, does not care to be restored to the degener-ate. So the Scholiasts understood it. “ Excidit: sci- licet animis. Curat reponi: i. e. restitui ipsis animis deterioribus, i. e. minus bonis quam prius.” (Porph.) Acron gives the same explanation, and notioes the opposite statement of Virgil (Aen. ii. 367) :—

“ Quondam etiam victis redit in praecordia virtus.
